l and nonmaterial harm historically done to black people, and still felt today, must be acknowledged. The idea that programs available to all people will benefit black people is demonstratively untrue, and the alternatives presented in America in Denial will generate much-needed conversations.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2024) 0aAfrican AmericansxSocial conditions. 0aAfrican Americans--Social conditions. 0aElectronic books. 0aEqualityzUnited States. 0aPolitical planningzUnited States. 0aRace discriminationxGovernment policyzUnited States. 0aRace discriminationzUnited States. 0aRace discrimination--Government policy--United States. 0aRace discrimination--United States. 4aAfrican American Studies : African American Studies. 4aAmerican Studies : American Culture. 4aPolitics and Law : Political Science. 4aPublic Policy : Public Policy. 4aSociology : Sociology. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Discrimination & Race Relations.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package 2021z978311149169140uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978143848298940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781438482989423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781438482989/original  a978-3-11-149169-1  SUNY Press eBook Package 2021b2021  aGBV-deGruyter-alles